WEBVTT

00:00:06.970 --> 00:00:07.390
PROFESSOR: Hi.

00:00:07.390 --> 00:00:08.950
Welcome back to recitation.

00:00:08.950 --> 00:00:11.450
We've been talking about
antidifferentiation or

00:00:11.450 --> 00:00:15.310
integration by substitution
and also by a method that

00:00:15.310 --> 00:00:17.670
Professor Jerison called,
advanced guessing.

00:00:17.670 --> 00:00:21.300
So I have a few problems up
on the board behind me.

00:00:21.300 --> 00:00:23.770
Three antiderivatives
for you to compute.

00:00:23.770 --> 00:00:28.030
So the first one is e to the
2x times cosine of the

00:00:28.030 --> 00:00:31.550
quantity 1 minus
e to the 2x dx.

00:00:31.550 --> 00:00:37.080
The second one is 4x times the
quantity 5x squared minus 1

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:40.240
raised to the 1/3 power.

00:00:40.240 --> 00:00:43.040
And the third one
is tan of x dx.

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:45.780
So why that you spend a few
minutes, try to compute those

00:00:45.780 --> 00:00:47.990
antiderivatives yourself,
come back and we

00:00:47.990 --> 00:00:49.240
can see how you did.

00:00:57.430 --> 00:00:59.640
All right, so welcome back.

00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:02.150
We have these three
antiderivative, so let's take

00:01:02.150 --> 00:01:03.140
them in order.

00:01:03.140 --> 00:01:09.020
So this first one that I wrote
is the antiderivative of e to

00:01:09.020 --> 00:01:13.250
the 2x times cosine
of the quantity 1

00:01:13.250 --> 00:01:17.240
minus e to the 2x dx.

00:01:17.240 --> 00:01:21.250
So this problem seems to me like
a good candidate for a

00:01:21.250 --> 00:01:22.280
substitution.

00:01:22.280 --> 00:01:25.790
So we have this clear
sort of nested

00:01:25.790 --> 00:01:27.100
function thing going on.

00:01:27.100 --> 00:01:31.360
We have cosine of 1
minus e to the 2x.

00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:33.980
And then out front we have
something that looks a lot

00:01:33.980 --> 00:01:36.720
like the derivative of this
1 minus e to the 2x.

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:39.080
So I'm going to try this
with substitution then.

00:01:39.080 --> 00:01:41.880
And I think there are, you
know, a few choices of

00:01:41.880 --> 00:01:45.140
substitution but a natural one
is to sort of find the most

00:01:45.140 --> 00:01:47.540
complicated inside piece.

00:01:47.540 --> 00:01:49.950
So in this case, that's
this whole thing, 1

00:01:49.950 --> 00:01:51.500
minus e to the 2x.

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:53.352
So I'm going to take for my
substitution, I'm going to

00:01:53.352 --> 00:02:01.620
take u equals 1 minus
e to the 2x.

00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:09.570
And so that means du is equal
to minus 2 e to the 2x dx.

00:02:09.570 --> 00:02:12.090
OK, so that's my substitution.

00:02:12.090 --> 00:02:14.460
And when I put my substitution
into this

00:02:14.460 --> 00:02:15.720
integral, what do I get?

00:02:15.720 --> 00:02:22.050
Well, so I have cosine of 1
minus e to the 2x just becomes

00:02:22.050 --> 00:02:23.300
cosine of u.

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:30.290
Now e to the 2x dx,
that's very, very

00:02:30.290 --> 00:02:32.610
close to this du here.

00:02:32.610 --> 00:02:36.330
So what's different is that
here I have a minus 2.

00:02:36.330 --> 00:02:43.070
So actually e to the 2x dx
is du divided by minus 2.

00:02:43.070 --> 00:02:48.890
So this is cosine u times
du divided by minus 2.

00:02:48.890 --> 00:02:52.060
Now another way to get to this
point is you could solve this

00:02:52.060 --> 00:02:56.790
equation for dx and substitute
it in and also solve this

00:02:56.790 --> 00:02:59.990
equation for e to the 2x and
substitute it in and things

00:02:59.990 --> 00:03:07.120
should work out more or less the
same if you try that out.

00:03:07.120 --> 00:03:09.420
So actually you won't even
need to make that second

00:03:09.420 --> 00:03:09.910
substitution.

00:03:09.910 --> 00:03:11.770
You'll just get some nice
cancellation there.

00:03:11.770 --> 00:03:13.450
It's even simpler than
what I just said.

00:03:13.450 --> 00:03:15.820
OK, so we do this
antiderivative, we've made

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:16.840
this substitution.

00:03:16.840 --> 00:03:18.220
So now we have just the

00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:20.990
antiderivative of a cosine function.

00:03:20.990 --> 00:03:22.480
All right, well that's
not that bad.

00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:25.540
Because we know that the
derivative of sine is cosine.

00:03:25.540 --> 00:03:28.450
So the antiderivative
of cosine is sine.

00:03:28.450 --> 00:03:32.010
So this is equal to-- so that
minus 2, that 1 over minus 2

00:03:32.010 --> 00:03:34.130
is just going to stick around.

00:03:34.130 --> 00:03:40.820
So it's 1 over minus 2 sine of
u plus a constant of course,

00:03:40.820 --> 00:03:41.618
plus an arbitrary constant.

00:03:41.618 --> 00:03:45.530
And OK, and so, but my original
function was in terms

00:03:45.530 --> 00:03:48.990
of x, so I want to bring
everything back in terms of x.

00:03:48.990 --> 00:03:53.640
And so I need to substitute
back in, get rid of u and

00:03:53.640 --> 00:03:54.420
replace it with x.

00:03:54.420 --> 00:03:59.240
So here that's a, I'll just go
back to what my substitution

00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:01.600
was and I replace all
my u's with it.

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:14.030
So this is minus 1/2 sine the
quantity 1 minus e to the 2x

00:04:14.030 --> 00:04:15.250
plus a constant.

00:04:15.250 --> 00:04:20.430
All right, so this is the
antiderivative of this first

00:04:20.430 --> 00:04:21.980
expression here.

00:04:21.980 --> 00:04:25.120
OK, so now, how about
the second one?

00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:27.750
So the second one, we could
also do it with a

00:04:27.750 --> 00:04:28.310
substitution.

00:04:28.310 --> 00:04:33.570
This is also sort of a prime
suspect for advanced guessing.

00:04:33.570 --> 00:04:39.120
So we see here that we have
some, this polynomial raised

00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:39.680
to some power.

00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:42.750
So this is 5x squared
minus 1 to the 1/3.

00:04:42.750 --> 00:04:46.850
So how can we get from a
derivative, something like 5x

00:04:46.850 --> 00:04:48.890
squared minus 1 quantity
to the 1/3?

00:04:48.890 --> 00:04:53.010
Well if you started off with 5x
squared minus 1 to the 4/3

00:04:53.010 --> 00:04:56.750
thirds and took a derivative,
you would have this 5x squared

00:04:56.750 --> 00:04:58.840
minus 1 to the 1/3 coming out.

00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:00.870
And you would also have some
stuff coming out in front by

00:05:00.870 --> 00:05:01.620
the chain rule.

00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:02.990
Well what kind of stuff?

00:05:02.990 --> 00:05:06.360
Well you know, it would be
some derivative of this

00:05:06.360 --> 00:05:09.130
quadratic polynomial, which
would be some linear

00:05:09.130 --> 00:05:09.270
polynomial.

00:05:09.270 --> 00:05:10.810
And indeed, that
kind of matches

00:05:10.810 --> 00:05:11.860
what we have out front.

00:05:11.860 --> 00:05:21.940
So a good guess for advanced
guessing, is that we can look

00:05:21.940 --> 00:05:28.770
at-- so d over dx of
5x squared minus 1

00:05:28.770 --> 00:05:32.100
quantity to the 4/3.

00:05:32.100 --> 00:05:35.840
So OK, so this derivative we can
compute by the chain rule.

00:05:35.840 --> 00:05:43.000
So this is 4/3 times
5x squared minus

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:45.830
1 to the 1/3 times--

00:05:45.830 --> 00:05:47.820
OK, so now I need to do the
chain rule, I need to take the

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:49.110
derivative of the inside.

00:05:49.110 --> 00:05:49.820
Well that's--

00:05:49.820 --> 00:05:53.340
OK, so the minus 1 gets killed
by the derivative, so 5x

00:05:53.340 --> 00:05:57.020
squared, that becomes 10x.

00:05:57.020 --> 00:06:06.530
So I can rewrite this as 40x
over 3 times 5x squared minus

00:06:06.530 --> 00:06:09.960
1 to the 1/3.

00:06:09.960 --> 00:06:13.320
So this looks very much like
the thing that we were

00:06:13.320 --> 00:06:13.846
interested in.

00:06:13.846 --> 00:06:13.862
Right?

00:06:13.862 --> 00:06:13.942
We were-- where'd it go?

00:06:13.942 --> 00:06:15.192
Oh, here it is.

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:19.340
And the thing we were trying
to antidifferentiate.

00:06:19.340 --> 00:06:23.410
So the difference is just this
constant out front is a little

00:06:23.410 --> 00:06:24.170
bit different.

00:06:24.170 --> 00:06:27.750
So here I have 4, whereas
when I took this

00:06:27.750 --> 00:06:29.820
derivative I had 40/3.

00:06:29.820 --> 00:06:31.910
So I need to correct for that.

00:06:31.910 --> 00:06:34.760
And the correction is just to
say, instead of starting with

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:38.080
this 5x squared minus 1 to the
4/3, I need to start with some

00:06:38.080 --> 00:06:41.290
multiple of it to make
the constant work out

00:06:41.290 --> 00:06:42.060
right in the end.

00:06:42.060 --> 00:06:46.710
So in this case I was off by a
multiple of 10/3, so I need to

00:06:46.710 --> 00:06:49.870
correct by multiplying
through by 3/10.

00:06:49.870 --> 00:06:53.200
So we get that the
antiderivative that we want.

00:06:53.200 --> 00:07:01.380
The antiderivative of 4x times
the quantity 5x squared minus

00:07:01.380 --> 00:07:07.785
1 to the 1/3 dx is equal
to, well it's

00:07:07.785 --> 00:07:12.880
equal to 3/10 of this.

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:18.910
5x squared minus 1 to the 4/3.

00:07:18.910 --> 00:07:22.030
OK, so that's our second
antiderivative, which we got

00:07:22.030 --> 00:07:23.670
by advanced guessing.

00:07:23.670 --> 00:07:24.960
Now let's look at
the third one.

00:07:24.960 --> 00:07:27.250
So the third one is tan x.

00:07:27.250 --> 00:07:30.600
Now I sort of promised you by
asking this question in this

00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:34.030
section on substitution that
there's, you know, some

00:07:34.030 --> 00:07:35.410
substitution you can make.

00:07:35.410 --> 00:07:38.700
But it's not sort of obvious
just from looking at tan x

00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:40.700
what should be substituted
where.

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:43.310
At least it isn't
obvious to me.

00:07:43.310 --> 00:07:45.570
But one thing that can help
often when you don't

00:07:45.570 --> 00:07:47.760
immediately see a substitution,
is to try

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:50.100
rewriting things in
equivalent ways.

00:07:50.100 --> 00:07:52.280
So sometimes you can do some
algebra or some other

00:07:52.280 --> 00:07:53.220
manipulation.

00:07:53.220 --> 00:07:56.220
In this case there's a very
simple sort of rewriting that

00:07:56.220 --> 00:07:56.620
you can do.

00:07:56.620 --> 00:07:59.420
Which is that tangent of x can
be expressed in terms of sine

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:00.520
and cosine of x.

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:07.530
So we can rewrite the
antiderivative of tan x dx as

00:08:07.530 --> 00:08:18.090
integral sine x over
cosine x dx.

00:08:18.090 --> 00:08:21.170
OK, so now what do we see?

00:08:21.170 --> 00:08:26.690
So, I see in the denominator
a cosine of x.

00:08:26.690 --> 00:08:30.610
And then up top I have
a sine x dx.

00:08:30.610 --> 00:08:36.050
So sine x dx, that's really
close to the differential of

00:08:36.050 --> 00:08:38.310
cosine of x.

00:08:38.310 --> 00:08:40.990
So I'm going to try
this substitution.

00:08:40.990 --> 00:08:44.560
And I'm going to try
the substitution u

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:46.310
equals cosine x.

00:08:46.310 --> 00:08:51.500
So if I make the substitution
I get du is equal to

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:55.900
minus sine x dx.

00:08:55.900 --> 00:08:59.000
Which is, OK, so now if I plug
these values in with this

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:06.585
substitution, this integral
becomes the integral, well

00:09:06.585 --> 00:09:14.190
it's minus 1 or minus
du over u.

00:09:14.190 --> 00:09:20.280
That's a nice simple
antiderivative to have. So

00:09:20.280 --> 00:09:21.590
we've seen this before.

00:09:21.590 --> 00:09:23.910
So this is just a logarithm.

00:09:23.910 --> 00:09:26.430
So the minus sine
comes out front.

00:09:26.430 --> 00:09:30.230
So this is minus ln
of the absolute

00:09:30.230 --> 00:09:32.490
value of u plus a constant.

00:09:32.490 --> 00:09:35.510
And now we had this, that
u was cosine of x.

00:09:35.510 --> 00:09:41.860
So this is minus ln of the
absolute value of cosine of x

00:09:41.860 --> 00:09:42.910
plus a constant.

00:09:42.910 --> 00:09:44.780
Now this should look a
little bit familiar.

00:09:44.780 --> 00:09:47.440
Because in one of Christine's
recitations earlier, she had

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:50.350
you compute the derivative
of ln of cosine x.

00:09:50.350 --> 00:09:52.960
And in that case you saw that
that derivative was equal to

00:09:52.960 --> 00:09:54.360
minus tangent of x.

00:09:54.360 --> 00:09:57.520
Just like it should be.

00:09:57.520 --> 00:09:59.150
So, all right, so there we go.

00:09:59.150 --> 00:10:04.110
That was three examples of
antidifferentiation by

00:10:04.110 --> 00:10:06.070
substitution and advanced
guessing.

00:10:06.070 --> 00:10:08.050
So I'll leave you with that.